{"title_page": "David di Donatello", "text_new": "{{short description|Annual Italian film awards ceremony}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name        = David di Donatello Awards\n| current_awards = 65th David di Donatello Awards\n| image       = File:David di Donatello miglior canzone originale- Alessandro Nelson Garofalo.jpg\n| imagesize   = 200px\n| caption     = A David di Donatello awarded in 2014\n| description = The best of Italian and foreign motion picture productions\n| date        = {{start date and age|1955}}\n| country     = Italy\n| presenter   = ''Accademia del Cinema Italiano'' (Academy of Italian Cinema)\n| year        = 5 June 1956\n| website     = {{URL|www.daviddidonatello.it}}\n}}\n\nThe '''David di Donatello Awards''', named after [[David (Donatello)|Donatello's ''David'']], are film awards given out each year by the ''[[Accademia del Cinema Italiano]]'' (The Academy of Italian Cinema). There are 24 award categories as of 2006. \n\nIt is the [[Italy|Italian]] equivalent to the American [[Academy Awards]] and ranks among top-tier awards such as the ''Premio Regia Televisiva'' for television, the ''Premio Ubu'' for stage performances, the [[Sanremo Music Festival]] for music and the annual [[Venice Film Festival]].\n\n== History ==\nFollowing the same criteria of the [[Academy Awards]], the ''David di Donatello'' Awards (known by the moniker \"Donatellos\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Oscar's Foreign Cousins|url=https://variety.com/1998/more/news/oscar-s-foreign-cousins-1117489265/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=Variety Media|date=December 9, 1998|accessdate=March 26, 2016}}</ref>) were established in 1955 and first awarded in Rome on July 5, 1956.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Laviosa|first1=Flavia|title=David di Donatello 1956\u20132016: Sixty Years of Awards|journal=Journal of Italian Cinema and Media Studies|date=January 29, 2015|url=http://www.intellectbooks.co.uk/MediaManager/File/New%20David%20di%20Donatello%20CFP.pdf|accessdate=March 25, 2016|trans-title=Call for Papers|publisher=Intellect|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017145833/http://www.intellectbooks.co.uk/MediaManager/File/New%20David%20di%20Donatello%20CFP.pdf|archive-date=October 17, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Created by a cultural club (then called The Open Gate), the aim was to honour the best of each year's Italian and foreign films.\n\nSimilar prizes had already existed in Italy for about a decade (for example, the ''Silver Ribbons''), but these were voted for by film critics and journalists. However, the Donatellos have been and are awarded by the people in the industry: screenwriters, performers, technicians, producers and so on.\n\nAfter Rome, from 1957 to 1980, the ceremonies were held at the Greek Theatre in Taormina, during [[Taormina Film Fest]], then twice in Florence, and finally returned to Rome, always with the support of the President of the Republic and now with the collaboration of the Rome City Council Cultural Policies Department.  During the years the ceremony was held in Taormina during the 1950s, it was organized by journalist and film producer Michael Stern who later went on to found The Michael Stern Parkinson's Research Foundation in New York City.\n\nThe founding organization, now called the ''[[Accademia del Cinema Italiano]]'' is fully functional and works in concert with and thanks to the contribution of the Italian Ministry of the Performing Arts and the Ministry for Cultural Properties and Activities.\n\nThe presidents have successively been Italo Gemini (the founder), Eitel Monaco and [[Paolo Grassi]]. Currently, it is presided over by Gian Luigi Rondi who has worked with the organization since its inception.\n\nThe prizes are awarded primarily to Italian films, with a category dedicated to foreign language films.\n\n==Presidents==\n[[File:David di Donatello a Ciampi.jpg|thumb|150px|[[President of Italy|Italian President]] [[Carlo Azeglio Ciampi|Ciampi]] shows the prize at the 2005 awards ceremony.]]\nHere is a list of presidents of the [[Accademia del Cinema Italiano|Academy of Italian Cinema]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:50%\"\n|-\n! width=\"8%\"| President\n! width=\"1%\"|Start\n! width=\"1%\"| End \n! width=\"8%\"| Notes\n|-\n| [[Italo Gemini]]\n| 1955\n| 1970\n|\n|-\n| [[Eitel Monaco]]\n| 1971\n| 1977\n|\n|-\n| [[Paolo Grassi]]\n| 1978\n| 1980\n|\n|-\n| [[Gian Luigi Rondi]]\n| 1981\n| 2016\u2020\n| President for Life since 2009\n|-\n| [[Giuliano Montaldo]]\n| 2016\n| 2017\n| Acting \n|-\n| [[Piera Detassis]]\n| 2018\n| ''now''\n| First female to hold the office\n|-\n|}\n\n\u2020 <small>Died in office. </small>\n\n==Trophy==\nThe trophy is in the form of a gold [[David (Donatello)|David]] statuette replica of Donatello's famous sculpture, on a square malachite base with a gold plaque recording the award category, year and winner.\n\nThe 1956 ''David'' by [[Bulgari]], awarded to [[Gina Lollobrigida]] for ''Beautiful but Dangerous'' was auctioned at [[Sotheby's]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gold and malachite 'David'|url=http://www.sothebys.com/en/auctions/ecatalogue/2013/magnificent-jewels-and-noble-jewels-ge1302/lot.647.html|publisher=Sotheby's}}</ref>\n\n==Award categories==\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Film]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Director]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best New Director]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Script|David di Donatello for Best Screenplay]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Producer]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Actress]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Actor]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Supporting Actress]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Supporting Actor]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Cinematography]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Score]]\n* David di Donatello for Best Original Song\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Sets and Decorations|David di Donatello for Best Set Designer]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Costumes]]\n* David di Donatello for Best Makeup\n* David di Donatello for Best Hair Design\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Editing]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Sound]]\n* David di Donatello for Best Visual Effects VFX\n* David di Donatello for Best Documentary Feature\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Foreign Film]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Short Film]]\n* David Giovani Award\n\n==Retired awards==\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Foreign Director]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Foreign Actor]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best Foreign Actress]]\n* [[David di Donatello for Best European Film]]\n\n==Statistics==\n===Multiple prize winning actors===\nWith 7 [[awards]] each, [[Vittorio Gassman]], [[Alberto Sordi]] and [[Margherita Buy]] are the actors who won the most Davids,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ufficiostampa.rai.it/dl/UfficioStampa/Articoli/DAVID-DI-DONATELLO-LA-STORIA-81d58410-7e77-4255-92db-373f094a1770.html|title=DAVID DI DONATELLO: LA STORIA|publisher=rai.it|language=it|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.altrospettacolo.it/david-di-donatello-2018-storia-vincitori/|title=David di Donatello 2018, 63 anni di Oscar del Cinema italiano|publisher=altrospettacolo.it|language=it|quote=Tra gli attori pi\u00f9 premiati di sempre troneggiano Alberto Sordi e Vittorio Gassman, entrambi a quota 7 David, vinti sempre come migliori attori protagonisti. La Meryl Streep del Cinema italiano \u00e8 invece Margherita Buy, che ne ha vinti altrettanti (su 16 candidature)|date=18 March 2018|accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> Updated at [[:it:David di Donatello 2018v|2018 David di Donatello]] (63 editions).\n{{legend|pink|Women}} \n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=50% style=\"font-size:100%; text-align:center;\"\n!rowspan=2 width=200px|Actor\n!colspan=2 width=100px|Leading\n!colspan=2 width=100px|Supporting\n!colspan=2 width=100px|Total\n|-\n!width=50px|W !!width=50px|N\n!width=50px|W !!width=50px|N\n!width=50px|W !!width=50px|N\n|-\n|align=left bgcolor=pink|[[Margherita Buy